******
[2]
Date: Tue 20 Mar 2018
Source: Independent [edited]
https://independent.ng/strange-disease-surfaces-in-katsina-school-kills-8-students/


A strange disease described, as 'mysterious epidemic' on [Mon 19 Mar 2018], struck Government Science Secondary School, Kurfi, in Katsina State and killed about 8 students of the school. The development was said to have forced the State Board for Science and Technical Education to shut down the school indefinitely and send its students home.

A senior government appointee of the board, who preferred to be anonymous confirmed the outbreak in the school, said the board closed the school to avoid the spreading of the epidemic to other students. "We have closed down the school indefinitely to avoid the spreading of the epidemic to other students. Measures are on top gear to vaccinate students of other schools to stop similar incident," the source said.

This is even as the State Assembly slammed the Board for the closure of the school, saying the action of the Board was capable of spreading the epidemic. Kabiru Lawal, a lawmaker representing Kurfi constituency at the Katsina House of Assembly, who confirmed the incident to his colleagues during plenary on [Mon 19 Mar 2018], under Matters of Public Importance, called for urgent attention by government. He said, "I am urging the House to step in. The epidemic has now forced the school authority to close the school down and send students back home."

Other lawmakers in the Assembly also claimed that similar epidemic occurred in their constituencies. Garba Useini, representing Kafur Constituency and Bishir Mamman of Dutsin-ma constituency, informed the House that the epidemic has broken down in their respective constituencies, but they could not ascertained the numbers of casualties recorded.

Presiding over the plenary, Abubakar Kusada, the speaker of the assembly, directed the House Committees on Education and that of Health to conduct a thorough investigation on the incident and report back to the House for urgent action.

[byline: Sardauna Francis]

