******
[3]
Date: Sun 18 Mar 2018 2:00AM
Source: Daily Trust [edited]
https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/8-more-persons-die-of-meningitis-in-katsina.html


A total of 8 more deaths have been recorded as the meningitis outbreak spreads in Jibia Local Government Area of Katsina State. Up to 2 weeks ago, 7 persons died in the same council just as several others were hospitalised.

Sources said the recent deaths were recorded between [Mon 12 Mar 2018] and [Thu 15 Mar 2018] this week. The permanent secretary in the Ministry of Health, Dr Kabir Mustapha, confirmed the deaths, saying 7 persons died at home and that only one death was recorded at the hospital. He said a planned vaccination is on the way for people of the area.

[byline: Habibu Umar Aminu]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Katsina State is located in north west Nigeria (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Katsina_State). Kurfi, where the 8 students died of an undiagnosed disease, is one of 34 Local Government Areas (LGAs) in Katsina State, with a population of 117 581 in 2006 (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kurfi). Kafur and Dutsin-Ma are other LGAs in Katsina State, where lawmakers (see news report #2 above) in the State Assembly also say "the epidemic has broken down in their respective constituencies". Jibia is another LGA in Katsina State, where 8 died of meningitis, the type not being specified in the news report (see news report #3 above). A map showing the location of LGAs in Katsina State and the location of Katsina State on Nigeria can be found at https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Map-of-Katsina-State-Showing-the-Location-of-Dutsin-Ma_fig1_263809397.

Earlier this month [March 2018], ProMED-mail reported a meningitis outbreak in the adjacent Jigawa State (ProMED-mail post Meningitis - Nigeria: fatal 20180307.5672461).

Northern Nigeria lies within the African meningitis belt, the semi-arid areas of sub-Saharan Africa where epidemics of meningococcal meningitis recur each year during the hot, dry season, between December and June. _Neisseria meningitidis_ serogroup A has been the main cause of epidemic meningococcal disease in this region (http://www.who.int/csr/resources/publications/meningitis/whoemcbac983.pdf). However, since the introduction of the meningococcal A conjugate vaccine in countries of the African meningitis belt, beginning in 2010, WHO has noted a decrease in the number of cases of meningitis; in fact, the number of cases in 2013 was the lowest recorded during the epidemic season in the last 10 years (http://www.who.int/csr/don/2013_06_06_menin/en/), and _N. meningitidis_ serogroup A was noted to be no longer the predominant pathogen, having been replaced by other serogroups, notably serogroup C, and other bacterial species.

Although the organisms causing the current meningitis outbreaks in Jigawa State or in Jibia LGA in Katsina State are not given, it may very well be meningococcus serogroup C, which caused an outbreak in Nigeria in 2017 (see also's below). ProMed-mail would appreciate more details concerning the meningitis outbreaks in Jigawa State or in Jibia LGA in Katsina State and the undiagnosed outbreaks in Kurfi, Kafur and Dutsin-Ma LGAs in Katsina State from knowledgeable sources.

Maps of Nigeria can be seen at http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/nigeria.pdf and https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5707401,617. A map of the African meningitis belt can be found at http://img.static.reliefweb.int/sites/reliefweb.int/files/resources/A592137EAFA85677C1256F2D0047FD68-af_menen.jpg. - Mod.ML]
